Detailed Description

Module OBEX is APOXI's API layer which enables applications to access and provide services based on the OBject EXchange Protocol OBEX.

Purpose and design goals

  • Provide a common application interface for sending and receiving objects via OBEX over different transport media, for example IrDA, Bluetooth and USB

  • Specify transport media and optional parameters using an URL-like string format derived from JSR-82 connection strings

  • Allow streaming of object data when sending and receiving

  • Facilitate adding of new transport protocols without having to change APOXI OBEX or even application code (apart from address strings)

  • Provide decoupling of application- and transport stack execution contexts

Concepts

The following paragraphs describe some general ideas which affect multiple classes and are therefore hard to explain from within class documentation.

OBEX URL's

OBEX URL's are passed as parameters to the Open() method of servers and clients. They are used to specify the transport protocol, the type of service offered by a server or requested by a client and optional transport-specific parameter such as Bluetooth security settings.

The following grammar of the OBEX URL is given in BNF:

  • 'literal'
    Literal (constant)

  • <production>
    Production (syntax expression).

  • [ <optional-part> ]
    Optional part.

  • { <repetitive-part> }
    Indicates <repetitive-part> may occur multiple times.

  • <alt1> | <alt2>
    Alternatives: May be alt1 or alt2 but not both.

  • <seq1> <seq2>
    Sequence: seq1 occurs first, then seq2.

  • <production> ':=' ... ;
    Defines the production <production>.

The overall structure is defined as following: 

    <obex-url> := <scheme> '://' [ <jsr-82-address> ] [ <obex-parameters> ] ;

    <scheme> := '*'
             |  <registered_transport_scheme>
             ;

Comment: <registered_transport_scheme> includes the return values of ObexAbstractTransport::GetUrlScheme() called on each transport instance registered with the ObexMngr singleton. The <jsr-82-address> is specified in the Java document and might be supported only partly, but the partial implementation must be compliant with the full syntax given in the JSR-82 specification.

The wildcard character '*' has a different meaning for client- and server addresses:

  • A wildcard server address will cause the server to bind all available transport protocols.

  • A wildcard client address will trigger a Transport Address Selection procedure asking the user to interactively select a transport protocol.

    <obex-parameters> := '{' <obex-parameter-list> '}' ;

    <obex-parameter-list> := <obex-parameter-assignment> { ',' <obex-parameter-assignment>  } ;

    <obex-parameter-assignment> := <obex-parameter-name> '=' <obex-parameter-value> ;

    <obex-parameter-name> := 'TARGET' ;

Comment: TARGET is a binary string which might be specified in ASCII or hex notation. It is used to register an OBEX server for a specific service addressed by the TARGET header and facilitates multiple OBEX serverss to share a single transport connection (OBEX multiplexing). When no TARGET header is specified, an associated server becomes the default OBEX server.

    <obex-parameter-value> := <obex-hex-string>
                           |  <obex-ascii-string>
                           ;

    <obex-hex-string> := 'H'{ <hex-digits-or-dash> }
                      ;

Comment: A hex string starts with 'H'. The following string literals may contain only an even number of hex digits and, optionally, dashes (only for readability, ignored by parser). Each two hex digits are converted into an octet, where the leftmost digit is the most significant nibble and the rightmost the least significant nibble.

Example:H'01-02-03-04' will be converted into 0x01, 0x02, 0x03, 0x04

    <obex-ascii-string> := ''' <any-char-but '''> '''

Comment: An ASCII string may contain any printable character but '''.

Example: 'SYNCML-SYNC'

Currently there is only one parameter which can occur in the list, but in the future it might be necessary to introduce new parameter types. In this case, the parameter assignments would be separated by commas: {TARGET=SYNCML-SYNC, NEW_PARAMETER=TRUE}. A comma indicates more parameter assignments are expected, so a parameter list defining a single parameter looks like this: {TARGET='SYNCML-SYNC'}.

OBEX Application

The OBEX application is a specialized MMI application which implements user interaction when a Transport Address Selection procedure must be performed.This can only happen when wildcard OBEX URL's like "*://" are used when opening a client connection and more than one Transport Adapter is available within the system. For more detailed information, please refer to the documentation of class ObexMngr.

Transport Adapters

Transport Adapters perform the adaptation between the generic transport interface of APOXI OBEX and the arbitrary interface of the individual transport protocol stacks. Therefore for each transport protocol stack to be used with APOXI OBEX a Transport Adapter must be implemented.

Transport Adapters register themselves with the central singleton class ObexMngr under a protocol name or 'scheme' and are then assigned a system-wide unique id of type ObexTransportId.

A Transport Adapter must at least implement the following interfaces:

  • ObexAbstractTransport Provides access to the protocol (OBEX) implementation by means of the method ObexAbstractTransport::GetProtocol(), which should return a pointer to the OBEX implementation for this transport. This is an instance of a class implementing the ObexLayer interface. Futhermore this class has to take care of address resolution, which means parsing of OBEX URL strings (possibly using the helper class ObexUrlParser) and constructing instances of address objects (pls. see paragraph below). These activities might involve asynchronous procedures like maintaining a Service Discovery Database in case of a server and Device Discovery / Service Discovery in case of a client.

  • ObexServerAddr and ObexClientAddr Represent server- and client addresses which have been constructed by the associated transport. The derives classes might contain transport- specific information like Bluetooth UUID's, RFCOMM ports and addresses or an IrDA device address and LSAP number. The base class supports run-time typing to facilitate save downcasting of addresses within a Transport Adapter implementation.

  • ObexLayer Contains the glue logic in between APOXI OBEX and the underlying transport stack. Public abstract methods must be implemented to forward outbound client requests and server responses to the protocol stack for sending, while received events must be forwarded towards APOXI by calling protected 'OnEventHasOccured()' methods.

  • AbstractTransport Represents the state of the hardware used by the transport protocol, for example an IrDA subsystem wich might be switched on and off at runtime. Must provide a method to poll the current state AbstractTransport::GetAvState()) and call AbstractTransport::OnAvStateChanged() each time the state changes. Other objects, for example ObexAbstractTransport then become observers of this class and will be notified when state changes occur.

Typedef Documentation

typedef SharedPtr< ObexAddress > ObexAddrPtr
 

Smartpointer used to manage ObexAddress instances.

This is an intrusive reference-counted shared pointer. The object instance to be managed by the pointer must be allocated with new and will be deleted automatically after the last referrer has passed away.

typedef UINT8 ObexAddrTypeId
 

This type id uniquely identifies a polymorphic class derived from either ObexClientAddr or ObexServerAddr.

typedef UINT8 ObexServerId
 

Uniquely identifies an OBEX service endpoint.

Used to represent the result of dispatching incoming server requests.

typedef UINT8 ObexTransportId
 

Transport Identifier uniquely identifies an ObexTransport implementation that has registered with ObexMngr.

enum ObexTransportMsgType
 

Message opcodes for ObexTransportMsg.

Enumerator:
ObexTrAvStateChanged  Indicates that the availability state has changed. Call GetAvState() on the transport to obtain the new state.
ObexTrEnableRejected  Indicates that a call to Enable() on the transport has failed. The transport state was left unaffected.
ObexTrSelectionResult  Indicates completion of a Transport Address Selection procedure.

In case of successful transport selection the transport id identifies the selected transport, the operation id identifies the procedure. In case of error it is set to ObexAbstractTransport::NoTransportId.

ObexResult ObexOppDataSinkPushServer::BindToMimeType (  MimeType  mime_type  )  [inline, inherited]
 

Binds the server to an additional mime type.

When the same type of processing is desired for several different mimetypes (for example, saving images to the filesystem) it is more convenient and also resource - saving to bind the same server to multiple mime types than running a seperate server instance for each mime type. This can be accomplished by calling BindToMimeType() on the server for each of the additional MIME types to be handled.

Caution: The server should be in closed state when calling this method. Each mime type may be registered by only one server.

Parameters:
mime_type MIME type identifier.
Returns:
ObexResult which evaluates to 'TRUE' in case of success, 'FALSE' otherwise.

Reimplemented from ObexOppServer.

ObexResult ObexObject::Init (  ObexBuffer &  source_buffer  )  [inline, inherited]
 

Initializes an ObexObject producing a valid request object.

If the object is the only referrer of the internally managed data, it is reinitialized. This is cheaper than overwriting it with a freshly created one because a dynamic memory allocation is saved. If multiple or no referrers exist, a new ObexObjectData object is allocated. After a successful call to Init(), the freshly initialized object is referenced only once and therefore writable.

Parameters:
source_buffer ObexBuffer to construct ObexObject instance from, this will take ownership of the data buffer and render 'source_buffer' invalid.

ObexResult ObexFtpServer::ProvideFolderListingEntriesFinished (   )  [inline, inherited]
 

Indicates the server that all folder listing entries are provided.

When all folder listing entries have been passed to the server by calling ProvideFolderListingEntry(...) for each entry, this method has to be invoked to continue the ongoing operation. This method indicates the server that all entires have been provided and thus the data transfer to the client can take place now.

Returns:
ObexResult which evaluates to 'TRUE' when the folder listing was scheduled for sending, 'FALSE' otherwise.

ObexResult ObexFtpServer::ProvideFolderListingEntry (  BOOLEAN  isFolder,
const String &  name,
const FolderListingEntryProperties &  properties
)  [inline, inherited]
 

Provides a folder listing entry to the server.

After OnProvideFolderListingEntries(...) has been invoked by the server to indicate that it is now ready to receive folder listing entries, this method has to be used to provide all entries of the current folder. The method has to be called for each entry, passing entry type, name and additional properties (if there are some). When all entries have been passed to the server the ongoing operation has to be continued by invoking ProvideFolderListingEntriesFinished(). This indicates the server that all entries have been provided and thus the data transfer to the client can take place now.

Parameters:
isFolder Specifies if the current entry is a file or folder entry. If the flag is set to 'TRUE', the entry will be handled as folder entry, if set to 'FALSE' the entry will be handled as file entry.
name The name of the entry (mandatory for Obex FTP).
properties All additional and optional Obex FTP attributes of the entry may be passed here, like the object size, access attributes, timestamps, etc.
Returns:
ObexResult which evaluates to 'TRUE' when the provided entry could be processed successfully and was scheduled for sending, 'FALSE' otherwise.
